      {
         "id": "SECTION_introduction",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Introduction\n\nOne of the axioms we studied in this chapter was that of commutativity (<htcite0>). Through it, we learned that the order of factors does not change the final result (product) of multiplication. Given this scenario, let us reflect on the learning process:",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "7a9c733b-ca13-40f5-8849-19012540b028",
                     "text": "Ernst, Dana",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 1: The Path of Knowledge</b><br /><br />Would it be possible to teach multiplication tables starting from nature and progressing to numbers?<br /><br />Could this approach improve people's understanding?</div></div></center></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_nature",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Nature\n\nUpon examining the map of North America (*Abya Yala*) presented in **Figure 1**, we can identify an extensive mountainous region. Within this area lies the city of Teotihuacan in Mexico, which we will now study.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><img src=\"images/Mapswire/continent_na-physical-map-north-america-robinson-269.jpg\" id=\"imgMoutains\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgMoutains', '0%')\" class=\"imgcenter\"/><b>Figure 1</b>: Map depicting mountain ranges in northern North America (Abya Yala). © Mapswire (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('dd4f3c8a-6624-4df5-93ac-37e0a4be9fdc'); return false;\"><i>Mapswire</i></a>).</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### Teotihuacan\n\nThe city of Teotihuacan emerged as an influential society across various Mesoamerican regions, inhabited from the late Preclassic period through much of the Classic period (between <htdate0> and <htdate1>) (<htcite0>; <htcite1>).\n\nSituated among numerous mountains due to its geographic location, the city's setting is illustrated in **Figures 2 and 3**:",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "4b6c8f3e-f8a2-4e41-b50c-230b81765ee4",
                     "text": "Cowgill, G. L.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "1997",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "cff9edbf-cd50-44cd-8ef7-54197d68c82b",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "-200",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  },
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "700",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"ChronologyTeotihuacan\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('ChronologyTeotihuacan', '0%')\" src=\"images/Teotihuacan/TeotihuacanGeneral.jpg\" class=\"imgcenter\"/><b>Figure 2</b>: Panoramic view of Teotihuacan. Photograph taken on <htdate0>, during a site visit.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2016",
                     "month": "10",
                     "day": "19"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "General view of Teotihuacan city. In this photo it is possible to observe different constructions in format Talud-Tablero, and in the background we have pyramidal structures representing sacred moutains.",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"ChronologyTeotihuacan2\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('ChronologyTeotihuacan2', '0%')\" src=\"images/Teotihuacan/TeotihuacanMountains.jpg\" class=\"imgcenter\" style=\"width:60%;\"/><b>Figure 3</b>: View of the Sun Pyramid in Teotihuacan, Mexico, from the Moon Pyramid. Photograph taken on <htdate0> during a site visit.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2016",
                     "month": "10",
                     "day": "19"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "General view of the Sun Pyramid and several smaller pyramids in the talud-tablero style. We can also observe mountains with varying slopes.",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### Modeling\n\nOur objective in this text is to precisely recreate these mountains, following the approach of the Teotihuacans and broader Mesoamerican peoples (<htcite0>). However, rather than constructing pyramidal structures as shown in **Figures 2 and 3**, we will accomplish this through drawings and mathematics.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "960e3a8e-3a60-4ee4-9df4-e2187489e3b9",
                     "text": "García Capistrán, H.",
                     "page": "pp. 144",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2018",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 2: Build Your Mountain</b><br /><br />Among the geometric shapes you know how to draw, which one most resembles a mountain?</div></div></center></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_shapes",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Shapes\n\nWhile we don't know your conclusion for **Reflection 2**, in our case we have identified triangles and pyramids as the ideal forms.\n\n#### Triangles\n\nVarious types of triangles exist (<htcite0>; <htcite1>), with one particular type being our focus: the isosceles triangle. This geometric figure features at least two equal angles, symmetry, and a broad base that gradually narrows to its apex (<htcite2>), as illustrated in **Chart 1**.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "f33dbf7c-924c-453f-bee5-a19388e75109",
                     "text": "Weisstein, Eric W.",
                     "page": "Triangle",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "72dcaa0f-07e3-41de-a637-c5b2f528dc33",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "61e568be-8a3a-4f53-bd2d-e9ce113cf68b",
                     "text": "Weisstein, Eric W.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"imgcenterresponsive\"><svg width=\"450\" height=\"300\"><polygon points=\"265,10 125,280 405,280\" style=\"fill:none;stroke:lightgreen;stroke-width:3\" /><text x=\"140\" y=\"270\" font-size=\"1.5em\">α</text><text x=\"370\" y=\"270\" font-size=\"1.5em\">α</text><g fill=\"none\" stroke=\"black\" stroke-width=\"1\"><path stroke-dasharray=\"5,5\" d=\"M265 14 l0 270\" /></g></svg></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Chart 1</b>: Isosceles triangle showing equal angles and sides.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### Pyramids\n\nAs two-dimensional shapes, triangles alone cannot fully represent the natural world. However, by combining triangles, we can better approximate our desired representation. **Figure 4** demonstrates how four united triangles form a pyramid (<htcite0>).",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "857f1df2-38ce-4da0-9444-686e16ac2314",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"pyramid\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('pyramid', '0%')\" src=\"images/HistoryTracers/pyramid.jpg\" class=\"imgcenter\"/><b>Figure 4</b>: Pyramid generated using a Python script available in our project repository (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('4f5657f4-4284-4e13-b90f-b0f1a7e50c68'); return false;\">Repository Scripts</a>).</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Before proceeding, we wish to emphasize an important clarification regarding terminology. While we compare Mesoamerican structures and mountains to pyramids, this doesn't literally make them pyramids. The more accurate designation for these Mesoamerican constructions would be \"sacred mountains\" with pyramidal forms (<htcite0>).",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "960e3a8e-3a60-4ee4-9df4-e2187489e3b9",
                     "text": "García Capistrán, H.",
                     "page": "pp. 144",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2018",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_slope",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Slope\n\nTriangles and pyramids help us approximate natural mountains. To better represent real mountains, we need to adjust our triangles, which requires studying their slope.\n\n#### Right Triangles\n\nLet us consider only one side of the isosceles triangle from **Chart 1**. Doing this gives us a right triangle (<htcite0>; <htcite1>), as shown in **Chart 2* with its labeled components:",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "56edda64-d96e-4106-b1f8-676a235b818c",
                     "text": "Weisstein, Eric W.",
                     "page": "Right triangle",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "72dcaa0f-07e3-41de-a637-c5b2f528dc33",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"imgcenterresponsive\"><svg height=\"245\" width=\"450\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\"><path d=\"M425 5 L75 200 L425 200 Z\" style=\"fill:none;stroke:green;stroke-width:3\" /><rect x=\"404\" y=\"179\" width=\"20\" height=\"20\" stroke=\"green\" fill=\"none\" stroke-width=\"3\" /><text x=\"125\" y=\"192\" font-size=\"1.5em\">α</text><text x=\"401\" y=\"45\" font-size=\"1.5em\">β</text><text x=\"235\" y=\"95\" font-size=\"2.5em\">c</text><text x=\"428\" y=\"120\" font-size=\"2.5em\">b</text><text x=\"265\" y=\"230\" font-size=\"2.5em\">a</text></svg></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Chart 2</b>: Right triangle with its components labeled.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "- **a**, **b** and **c**: The sides of the triangle. Sides **a** and **b** are called **legs**, while **c** is the **hypotenuse**.\n- **α**, **β**, and <i class=\"fa-regular fa-square\"></i>: The angles formed by the intersection of the sides. The square symbol ( <i class=\"fa-regular fa-square\"></i> ) marking the angle between the horizontal and vertical sides is called the **right angle**.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### Adjusting the Hypotenuse\n\nFrom **Chart 2**, we conclude that to increase the triangle's height, we must increase the length of side **b**. Consequently, this also increases the hypotenuse length **c**, as visualized in **Chart 3**.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><div class=\"htChart\"><canvas aria-label=\"chart\" id=\"chart1\" style=\"width:30em !important; height:20em !important;\"></canvas></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Chart 3</b>: Points from multiplication tables 0 through 9 connected to form straight lines. Chart created using <a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('b77ec8fc-c988-45f3-82f8-03b136bf1aa9'); return false;\">Chart JS</a> library.</div></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Note that for all lines in **Chart 3**, we maintain side **a** with constant values between 0 and 10. The only varying values are side **b** and, consequently, the hypotenuse length **c**.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><div class=\"first_steps_lab_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_lab question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-microscope\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_lab\"><b>Practice 1</b><br /><br />To further clarify our explanation, follow these steps:<br *><br />1. Click all titles <b>Table of X</b> (where <b>X</b> is a number between <b>0</b> and <b>9</b>) to hide lines.<br />2. Click each title individually to show the lines again.</div></div></center></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_line",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Zoom on Lines\n\nThe lines drawn on **Chart 3** were created following rules called mathematical formulas (<htcite0>). To better understand this process, let us recall how indigenous peoples made their sacred mountains in Mesoamerica.\n\n#### Rebuilding\n\nWhat we generally observe in archaeological sites, as shown in **Figures 2 and 3**, represents the final stage of a construction process that began with small structures. Additional structures were subsequently built on top of these until reaching the final form. We must not forget that in some cases, the final structure was built atop even older structures (<htcite1>), as shown in **Figura 5**.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "a84a6938-22ad-4fa4-9588-2d70f6aa1693",
                     "text": "Weisstein, Eric W.",
                     "page": "Formula",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "daae87a2-5fa9-43d1-88fb-6713b25d50d5",
                     "text": "Tuarez Mejia, L. F.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2023",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"imgCopanTemple\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgCopanTemple', '0%')\" src=\"images/Copan/Temple16Copan.png\" class=\"imgcenter\"/><b>Figure 1</b>: Sign at the Archaeological Site of Copán (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('1e007481-9bd3-4a09-ad4d-6e812fe79641'); return false;\">Instituto Hondureño de Antropologia e Historia, <htdate0></a>). Photo taken on <htdate1>, during a visit to the site.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2024",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  },
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2015",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "The image depicts the sequential construction phases of Temple 16, with later temples superimposed on earlier ones.",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### Unlinking Points\n\nFor construction, we use small blocks stacked on top of others. This replicates what we observe in natural processes occurring over millions of years (<htcite0>).\n\nBoth natural processes and human constructions involve repetitive steps connecting either elements or blocks of stone. To make this even clearer, we will remove the lines connecting points in **Chart 3**, leaving only the visible points in **Chart 4** below:",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "9b33bffc-ad77-472d-84a6-aa94946e8645",
                     "text": "Bird, P.",
                     "page": "pp. 1 - 14",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "1988",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><div class=\"htChart\"><canvas aria-label=\"chart\" id=\"chart2\" style=\"width:30em !important; height:20em !important;\"></canvas></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Chart 4</b>: Points from the zero to nine table. Chart created using <a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('b77ec8fc-c988-45f3-82f8-03b136bf1aa9'); return false;\">Chart JS</a>.</div></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "**Chart 4** exactly reproduces what we learned in this chapter. From this, we can observe:\n- When viewing the horizontal axis and approaching zero (where multiplication always yields the same result), the vertical points become closer to each other.\n- **Commutativity**: Points share the same vertical value when commutativity occurs. For example, the value 15 appears when multiplying 3 by 5 and 5 by 3.\n- All numbers appearing in the hypotenuse of a multiplication table also appear vertically in their factor's column.\n\nDespite having connected points in the tables we've been using, the multiplication results we've learned so far create disconnected (discrete) points. We will learn how to connect them in future chapters. For now, let's generalize these disconnected points.\n\n#### Repeated Sums\n\nWhen performing repeated sums, we are executing an operation called multiplication (<htcite0>). During our studies, we observed that these repeated sums can be represented in different ways. For example, to add the number 10 three consecutive times, we can express it as follows (<htcite1>):",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "eaa59295-fb80-4c33-b1e4-bcdf3c11dabf",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "5",
                        "day": "9"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "eaa59295-fb80-4c33-b1e4-bcdf3c11dabf",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "5",
                        "day": "9"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
